{
    "analysis": "None",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv into memory (pandas). For each file, return a compact summary only: total row count, min timestamp, max timestamp, top 20 unique values of the key name column (for metric.csv -> kpi_name, trace.csv -> trace_name, log.csv -> log_name, error_logs.csv -> show top 20 unique messages), and the list of unique cmdb_id values (limit display to first 50 if more). Also return the total number of unique cmdb_id per file. Store each full dataframe in kernel variables named df_metric, df_trace, df_log, df_error. Do not print full dataframes—only the requested aggregates. Limit each returned list to at most 20 items (50 for cmdb_id list cap)."
}

{
    "analysis": "From the prior summaries: metric.csv (148,984 rows) and trace.csv (34,636 rows) both cover the full incident window 2022-03-21 18:00:00+08:00 to 2022-03-21 18:29:00+08:00. log.csv and error_logs.csv also contain entries in that window. Many cmdb_id values exist across metrics/traces (services and pods such as adservice-0.., cartservice.., etc.). error_logs.csv shows a small set of components (sample: frontend-2, frontend-0, frontend-1, checkout...) and messages like 'severity: warning, message: failed to retriev...' which may be relevant. To narrow candidates we must follow the prescribed workflow: compute global thresholds (per component-KPI) using the full metric series, then extract incident-window data and detect anomalies. The next atomic step is to detect metric anomalies per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) using a global P95 threshold and report compact aggregates (counts and earliest anomaly times) so we can choose top faulty component-KPIs for deeper trace/log analysis.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the cached df_metric in kernel, do the following: 1) For each unique (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pair compute the global P95 threshold using all available rows for that pair (do NOT filter by time yet). 2) Filter df_metric to rows within the incident window 2022-03-21 18:00:00+08:00 through 2022-03-21 18:30:00+08:00 (inclusive). 3) For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute: anomaly_count = number of rows in the incident window where value >= P95; earliest_anomaly_timestamp = the minimum timestamp among those anomaly rows (if any); max_value_in_window; p95_threshold. 4) Return a compact table of the top 20 (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pairs sorted by anomaly_count desc (tie-breaker: earliest_anomaly_timestamp asc) with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, p95_threshold. Also store the full per-pair table in a kernel variable named metric_anomaly_summary. Limit returned rows to 20. Do not print raw dataframes beyond this summary."
}

{
    "analysis": "The metric anomaly summary shows many (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pairs—especially for adservice—have anomaly_count = 30 with earliest anomaly at 2022-03-21 18:00:00+08:00 and max_value equal to the global P95. That indicates continuous threshold breaches across the entire 30-minute window for those KPIs, making adservice a strong candidate. However, we must follow the workflow: locate consecutive anomaly sub-series (faults), filter out isolated 1-minute spikes, and then use traces/logs to pinpoint root cause components and reasons. The next step is fault identification: find consecutive anomaly intervals per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) within the incident window.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the cached df_metric and the previously computed p95 thresholds (from metric_anomaly_summary or recompute per (cmdb_id,kpi_name) using full series if needed), do the following: 1) Filter df_metric to the incident window 2022-03-21 18:00:00+08:00 through 2022-03-21 18:30:00+08:00 inclusive. 2) For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name), mark rows as anomaly if value >= that pair's global P95. 3) Identify consecutive anomaly runs (consecutive timestamps differing by 60 seconds) and record each run as a fault with: cmdb_id, kpi_name, fault_start_timestamp (first timestamp of run), fault_end_timestamp (last timestamp of run), duration_minutes (count of minutes in run), max_value_in_fault, p95_threshold. 4) Filter out runs shorter than 2 minutes (to remove isolated spikes). 5) Return a compact table of the top 20 faults sorted by duration_minutes desc (tie-breaker: max_value_in_fault desc) with the columns specified above. Also store the full faults table in kernel variable named metric_faults. Limit output to 20 rows."
}

{
    "analysis": "Previous metric analysis and fault identification found many long-running faults (>=2 minutes) spanning the full 18:00–18:29 window. Notable candidates: many adservice KPIs (multiple JVM/runtime and app request metrics) show continuous breaches starting at 2022-03-21 18:00:00+08:00; several node-* entries show system.disk.total anomalies across the window as well. This suggests at least one widespread, persistent problem affecting multiple services (adservice prominent) and possible node-level disk-related anomalies. To decide the root cause for the two distinct failures we must (a) use traces to find which service/container is the last faulty downstream in call chains, and (b) use logs/error_logs to confirm the reason. The immediate next atomic action is to analyze trace telemetry similarly to metrics: compute global per-(cmdb_id, trace_name) P95 thresholds using the full trace.csv, then detect anomalies in the incident window and produce a compact ranked summary of trace anomalies for localization.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using cached df_trace in the kernel, perform the following steps: 1) For each unique (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute the global P95 threshold using all rows for that pair (do NOT filter by time). 2) Filter df_trace to the incident window 2022-03-21 18:00:00+08:00 through 2022-03-21 18:30:00+08:00 inclusive. 3) For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) within the window, count anomaly_count = number of rows where value >= P95, and compute earliest_anomaly_timestamp (min of those timestamps), max_value_in_window, and p95_threshold. 4) Return a compact table of the top 20 (cmdb_id, trace_name) pairs sorted by anomaly_count desc (tie-breaker: earliest_anomaly_timestamp asc) with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, p95_threshold. Also include the total number of unique cmdb_id values present in that top-20 set. Store the full per-pair table in kernel variable trace_anomaly_summary. Limit returned rows to 20."
}

{
    "analysis": "Trace analysis showed many (cmdb_id, trace_name) pairs flagged as anomalous for the entire incident window (18:00–18:29), but a large fraction have P95=0 which makes those 'anomalies' uninformative by themselves. Metric faults show many long-running faults spanning the whole window, with adservice and several node-* disk metrics standing out. To separate the two distinct failures and find exact occurrence times and root components we need to correlate with logs/error_logs (these often show concrete errors and timestamps). The next step should therefore inspect error_logs and log.csv to find when error messages spike and which components produced them (this will help split the two failures and guide trace-level localization).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using cached df_error (error_logs.csv) perform a compact analysis: 1) Compute total message count and number of unique cmdb_id. 2) For each cmdb_id, produce message_count, earliest_message_timestamp, latest_message_timestamp; return top 20 cmdb_id rows sorted by message_count desc. 3) Aggregate error_logs by timestamp (per-minute) within the incident window 2022-03-21 18:00:00+08:00 through 2022-03-21 18:30:00+08:00 and return the per-minute counts for minutes that have count>0, sorted by timestamp (limit to top 50 rows). 4) Return top 20 unique message text samples overall (truncate messages to 200 chars) with counts. Store the full aggregated per-minute series in kernel variable error_logs_timeseries. Limit all returned lists/tables to at most 20 rows except the per-minute series which may be up to 50 rows."
}

{
    "analysis": "From the prior Executor outputs: metric analysis found many long-running faults (30-minute runs starting at 2022-03-21 18:00:00+08:00) across many KPIs—notably adservice JVM/runtime and many container start_time/system.disk totals on node-* entries. Trace analysis flagged many trace pairs as anomalous across the whole window but many had P95=0 (so they are not informative by simple >=P95 checks). Error logs show heavy and sustained warnings from frontend-0/1/2 throughout the whole window (total 2060 messages), with a notable per-minute spike at 2022-03-21 18:29:00+08:00 (163 messages). The observations so far: (1) Many metric 'faults' span the entire 18:00–18:29 window (may indicate baseline differences or pervasive anomalies), (2) Frontend nodes generated the bulk of error log messages, and (3) there is a clear error-log peak at 18:29 which may correspond to a second distinct failure. We have not yet localized the exact root cause component/time/reason for two separate failures. To make progress we must analyze normalized log KPIs (log.csv) to find which components had per-minute log-feature anomalies (e.g., log.error_count, log.row_count) and their earliest anomaly timestamps, so we can correlate with metric faults and trace anomalies.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the cached df_log in kernel, do the following atomic steps: 1) For each unique (cmdb_id, log_name) compute the global P95 threshold using the full series (do NOT filter by time). 2) Filter df_log to the incident window 2022-03-21 18:00:00+08:00 through 2022-03-21 18:30:00+08:00 inclusive. 3) For each (cmdb_id, log_name) within the window compute: anomaly_count = number of rows where value >= P95, earliest_anomaly_timestamp (min timestamp of those rows if any), max_value_in_window, p95_threshold. 4) Return a compact table of the top 20 (cmdb_id, log_name) pairs sorted by anomaly_count desc (tie-breaker earliest_anomaly_timestamp asc) with columns: cmdb_id, log_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, p95_threshold. 5) Store the full per-pair results in kernel variable 'log_anomaly_summary'. Limit returned rows to 20." 
}

{
    "analysis": "Previous steps established: (1) metric analysis found many long-running faults spanning the entire 18:00–18:29 window (notably many adservice JVM/runtime KPIs and several node system.disk.total entries), with the faults' earliest timestamps at 2022-03-21 18:00:00+08:00; (2) trace-level bulk anomalies exist but many trace P95 thresholds are 0, making those trivial and not useful as-is; (3) log.error_count global P95 is 0 for many services so those alarms are false-positives by the simple rule; (4) error_logs show frontend-0/1/2 emitted most messages throughout the window and a sharp spike at 2022-03-21 18:29:00+08:00 (163 messages) — suggesting two distinct events: a pervasive condition present from the window start (around 18:00) and a second spike/failure around 18:29. From here we need informative (non-trivial) trace anomalies (where P95>0) to localize which service/container is the downstream faulty participant for each failure, and then correlate with logs/metrics. The next atomic action is to surface only the informative trace anomaly records (P95>0) from the previously computed trace_anomaly_summary so we can see which services/traces have meaningful deviations and their earliest anomaly times.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the cached trace_anomaly_summary in kernel, filter rows where p95_threshold > 0 and anomaly_count > 0. Return a compact table of up to the top 20 rows sorted by anomaly_count desc (tie-breaker: earliest_anomaly_timestamp asc) with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, p95_threshold. Also return the number of unique cmdb_id in this filtered set and store the filtered DataFrame in kernel variable 'trace_anomaly_informative'. Limit output to 20 rows."
}

{
    "analysis": "We filtered trace anomalies to the informative subset (P95>0) and found ~40 rows across services such as cartservice2-0, frontend2-0, checkoutservice-1/0/2, paymentservice-2, and emailservice-* with sustained anomalies (many anomaly_count = 30 starting at 2022-03-21 18:00:00+08:00). Combined with previous findings: (a) metric_faults shows many long-running faults beginning at 18:00 (notably adservice JVM/runtime and several node.disk.total entries), and (b) error_logs show heavy frontend warnings across the window with a clear spike at 18:29. This suggests two distinct incidents: a pervasive problem that started around 18:00 and persisted for the whole window, and a second spike/failure around 18:29. To decide which faults are the true root causes (and at which level: node vs service vs pod) we must quantify severity of metric faults (how much they deviate from their P95) and rank them — the most severe deviations likely indicate the root cause level. The next step is to compute a severity score per metric fault (relative deviation from P95 when P95>0, or absolute severity flag when P95==0 and max>0) and return the top 20 faults by severity so we can determine whether node-level (disk) or service-level (adservice, checkout/cart chain) faults are dominant.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the cached metric_faults table in kernel, compute a severity score for each fault: if p95_threshold>0 then severity = (max_value_in_fault - p95_threshold) / p95_threshold; else if p95_threshold==0 and max_value_in_fault>0 set severity = a large number (e.g., 1e6) to indicate a strong absolute breach; else severity = 0. Add this severity column to metric_faults, then return a compact table of the top 20 faults sorted by severity descending (tie-breaker: duration_minutes desc) with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, fault_start_timestamp, duration_minutes, max_value_in_fault, p95_threshold, severity. Also return counts of how many of these top-20 are node-level (cmdb_id starts with 'node-') vs service/pod-level (others). Store the augmented DataFrame in kernel variable 'metric_faults_severity'. Limit the returned rows to 20." 
}

{
    "analysis": "We previously computed metric faults and assigned a severity score, but many top-severity entries were artifacts where p95_threshold == 0 and we set severity to a large constant (1e6). Trace analysis produced an informative subset (P95>0) implicating checkout/cart/email/payment chains starting at 2022-03-21 18:00:00+08:00. Error logs show heavy frontend warnings throughout the window and a clear spike at 2022-03-21 18:29:00+08:00. At this point we need to separate true metric deviations from threshold-artifacted ones: specifically identify metric faults whose p95_threshold > 0 (so relative severity is meaningful) and rank them by severity. This will let us pick the most significant non-artifact faults to localize the root cause components for the two failures (the long-running ~18:00 event and the spike at ~18:29).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the cached metric_faults_severity in kernel, filter rows where p95_threshold > 0 and severity > 0 (exclude rows where we set artificial severity for p95==0). Return a compact table of the top 20 rows sorted by severity desc (tie-breaker: duration_minutes desc) with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, fault_start_timestamp, duration_minutes, max_value_in_fault, p95_threshold, severity. Also return a small summary: number of rows in this filtered set, and counts of how many of these top-20 are node-level (cmdb_id starts with 'node-') vs pod/service-level (others). Store the filtered DataFrame in kernel variable 'metric_faults_real_severity'. Limit output to 20 rows."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have progressed through the required workflow: thresholds were computed from full series, the incident window was filtered, anomalies and consecutive fault runs were identified, and severity-ranking was applied. Key intermediate findings: (1) Many long-running metric \"faults\" span the entire window starting at 2022-03-21 18:00:00+08:00 (but many are artifacts where P95==0); (2) After excluding P95==0 artifacts, we found meaningful high-severity faults clustered at specific minutes: a clear cluster at 2022-03-21 18:14:00+08:00 affecting checkoutservice (jaeger/istio mesh metrics and app.grpc.mrt), paymentservice2-0 container FS and memory metrics (same minute), and (3) other notable short but severe faults: node-6 TCP retransmission at 2022-03-21 18:02:00+08:00 and node-5 CPU iowait at 2022-03-21 18:26:00+08:00. Error logs show frontend-0/1/2 produced the bulk of messages for the whole window and a pronounced spike at 2022-03-21 18:29:00+08:00 (163 messages), suggesting a second distinct failure around 18:29. At this point we have good candidates for two separate incidents but need to confirm the first failure’s exact root component and reason by listing all metric faults that started at 2022-03-21 18:14:00+08:00 (to see breadth and severity across components), so we can use traces/logs next to pick the most downstream faulty service/pod and the underlying resource cause.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the cached metric_faults_real_severity in the kernel, filter rows whose fault_start_timestamp equals '2022-03-21 18:14:00+08:00'. Return a compact table (limit 50 rows) with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, fault_start_timestamp, duration_minutes, max_value_in_fault, p95_threshold, severity. Also return the number of unique cmdb_id in this filtered set and the top 10 cmdb_id by count in this set. Store the filtered result in kernel variable 'faults_at_18_14'."
}

{
    "analysis": "From prior steps we computed global thresholds and identified metric faults and trace/log anomalies across the incident window. Key findings so far: \n- Many metric \"faults\" spanned the whole window starting 2022-03-21 18:00:00+08:00, but many were artifacts where P95==0 and thus not reliable alone. \n- After excluding p95==0 artifacts, a clear short but high-severity cluster occurred at 2022-03-21 18:14:00+08:00 affecting checkoutservice (several mesh/jaeger/istio counters and app.grpc.mrt) and paymentservice2-0 (container fs reads and memory-failure counters on node-6). The filtered set 'faults_at_18_14' shows multiple affected cmdb_id (checkoutservice-1, paymentservice2-0, checkoutservice-0, etc.). This cluster is likely one distinct failure. \n- Separately, error_logs show sustained frontend warnings across the entire window and a pronounced spike at 2022-03-21 18:29:00+08:00 (163 messages) — suggesting a second distinct failure around 18:29 that is log-dominated and frontend-centric. \nTo decide the root cause for the 18:14 event we need trace evidence to identify the most-downstream faulty service in the affected call chains (checkout -> payment -> email). Traces at that minute will tell us which service in the chain was actually faulty and whether paymentservice2-0 resource issues correlate with checkoutservice trace anomalies. Therefore the next step is to inspect traces at the 18:14 minute focused on checkout/payment/email-related trace names.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the cached df_trace in kernel, filter trace records to the single minute 2022-03-21 18:14:00+08:00. From those rows, select only trace_name values that contain any of the keywords 'checkout', 'payment', or 'email' (case-insensitive). Aggregate by (cmdb_id, trace_name) and compute: count (number of rows), mean(value), max(value), earliest_timestamp (min). Return a compact table of the top 20 (cmdb_id, trace_name) pairs sorted by count desc with the columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, count, mean_value, max_value, earliest_timestamp. Also store the full filtered trace-minute DataFrame in kernel variable 'trace_18_14'. Limit returned rows to 20."
}

{
    "analysis": "You filtered traces for the minute 2022-03-21 18:14:00+08:00 and found 312 trace rows; most duration/error metrics are zero, but several row_count metrics are non-zero (notably shippingservice2-0 with row_count=12 and multiple cartservice.* row_count=2–3). Metric-fault clustering at 18:14 implicates checkoutservice (many high-severity mesh/jaeger/istio metrics) and paymentservice2-0 container FS/memory-failure metrics on node-6. This indicates a focused incident at 18:14 involving the checkout -> payment -> email call chain (checkoutservice and paymentservice2-0 are prime suspects). Separately, error_logs show frontend warnings throughout the window and a sharp spike at 18:29:00+08:00 (163 messages), suggesting a second distinct failure around 18:29 centered on frontend components. To localize the 18:14 root cause we must identify which downstream service in the call chains actually shows request activity or abnormal trace metrics at that minute (row_count/duration/error non-zero), then correlate with the metric faults (which already pointed to checkoutservice and paymentservice2-0). The next step is to extract the informative trace rows at 18:14 that have non-zero signal (row_count/duration/error) so we can see which services are downstream and have activity/abnormalities.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the cached trace_18_14 DataFrame in the kernel, do the following atomic task: 1) Filter trace_18_14 to rows where trace_name (case-insensitive) contains any of: 'row_count', 'duration_p95', 'duration_mean', or 'error_rate' AND the value > 0. 2) Aggregate the filtered rows by (cmdb_id, trace_name) and compute: count (number of samples), mean(value) as mean_value, max(value) as max_value, earliest_timestamp (min). 3) Return a compact table of the top 20 aggregated rows sorted by max_value desc with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, count, mean_value, max_value, earliest_timestamp. 4) Also return the number of unique cmdb_id in this filtered set and store the filtered (pre-aggregated) DataFrame in kernel variable 'trace_18_14_nonzero'. Limit output to 20 rows."
}

